          "body": "The LORD shifts from vision to cross-examination. The rhetorical questions of verses 4-5 are an appeal to common sense: even a man who falls gets up; even someone who turns away turns back. Nature itself operates by the logic of return. Why, then, has this people turned away in continual apostasy — holding fast to deceit, refusing to return? The Hebrew word for 'continual apostasy' is meshuvah, the same word translated 'backsliding' elsewhere. It is not one act of defection but an entrenched posture. God has listened (qashav — leaned in, paid close attention) and heard: no one repents, no one says 'What have I done?', everyone has charged like a horse into battle — headlong, thoughtless, unstoppable. Then comes the animal comparison of verse 7, one of the most arresting in all of the prophets: the stork, the turtledove, the swift, and the thrush all know their appointed seasons and observe the time of their migration. These birds obey an instinct God embedded in them at creation. But My people — the covenant nation who received explicit divine instruction — do not know the ordinance of the LORD. The creation that cannot read is more obedient than the people who have the Torah."
