        "body": "God's cross-examination of the living people in verses 4-7 is built on an appeal to natural reason before it is an appeal to revelation. The rhetorical questions of verse 4 — does a man who falls not rise? does a man who turns away not return? — are appeals to observable human behavior. Even by the logic of instinct and self-interest, turning back when you have gone the wrong way is the obvious move. The question that follows — 'why then has this people turned away in continual apostasy?' (v. 5) — cannot be answered by natural reason, because natural reason does not behave this way. The apostasy is not merely sinful; it is irrational.\n\nThe irrational is then exposed by comparison with the instinctive. Four migratory birds — stork (chasidah), turtledove (tor), swift (sus, which is ironic because the same word in v. 6 describes a war horse), and thrush (agur) — all know their moed. The word moed is the covenant calendar word: appointed times, sacred seasons, the moments when Israel was to appear before the LORD and renew the covenant (Leviticus 23; Deuteronomy 16). These birds honor the time God built into creation. Israel, given explicit divine instruction about the times of covenant renewal, does not know the mishpat of the LORD — His rightful ordinance, His appointed governance of the covenant relationship.\n\nThe comparison is deliberately humbling. The Wisdom tradition (Job 12:7-8; Proverbs 6:6-8) regularly directs the arrogant to learn from creation. Jeremiah stands in that tradition, but the stakes are higher: this is not general moral instruction but a direct accusation that Israel has fallen below the level of an instinct-following bird. The stork honors the God-embedded order without being told; Israel has been told explicitly and refuses. This sets up the irony of verses 8-9 with devastating effect: if birds know their seasons better than Israel does, what exactly does Israel's 'wisdom' consist of?\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Meshuvah* (continual apostasy, v. 5) — from the root shuv (to turn/return), the same root as repentance (*teshuvah*). Apostasy and repentance are mirror images using the same word; to turn away is the opposite of to turn back. *Moed* (appointed seasons, v. 7) — the calendar of covenant assembly, not merely biological migration timing; its application to birds heightens the irony directed at Israel."
