        "title": "The lying pen — when Scripture-possession replaces Scripture-submission",
        "range": "8:8-12",
        "excerpt": "How can you say, 'We are wise, and the law of the LORD is with us'? But behold, the lying pen of the scribes has made it into a lie.",
        "body": "Jeremiah's indictment of the scribal class in verses 8-9 is one of the most penetrating critiques of religious intellectualism in the entire Old Testament. The scribes claim two things: (1) we are wise (chakhamim), and (2) the Torah is with us. Both claims are true in a formal sense — they were trained in wisdom literature, and they did possess and copy the Torah. The problem Jeremiah identifies is that these two claims have been inverted from their proper relationship. Wisdom was supposed to be derived from submission to the Torah; instead, the scribes have used their possession of the Torah as a credential for a wisdom that no longer serves the Torah's actual demands. The lying pen (sheqer saphar) has falsified the text — or, perhaps more likely in context, has produced legal interpretations and rulings that neutered the Torah's moral force while maintaining the appearance of fidelity to it.\n\nThe result (v. 9) is that the wise men are 'put to shame, dismayed, and caught' — three verbs of progressive entrapment. They have rejected the word of the LORD (the living prophetic word Jeremiah brings) in favor of the scribal tradition they have shaped. And so the verdict: 'what kind of wisdom do they have?' The question expects the answer: none. Wisdom that rejects divine revelation is not wisdom reconfigured — it is wisdom emptied. The same structure appears in Romans 1:22 ('professing to be wise, they became fools') and 1 Corinthians 1:19-20 ('I will destroy the wisdom of the wise'), but Jeremiah's version is sharper because it targets people who hold the actual text of Scripture while corrupting its application.\n\nVerses 10-12 widen the indictment from scribes to prophets and priests. Greed (batsa, greedy for gain) is the engine of the corruption — from the least to the greatest, everyone has made financial advantage the organizing principle of ministry. The false prophets treat the nation's catastrophic fracture (shever — a word used for the breaking of bones and the breaking of nations) with qalal — to make light of, to trivialize. This is not incompetence; it is malpractice. They know the wound is serious and they are minimizing it anyway, because 'Peace, peace' is what pays and what is welcomed. The capacity for shame (bush) would have checked them; having lost it, they cannot even recognize that their conscience has been cauterized. The verdict of verse 12 is therefore: they shall fall among those who fall at the time of their punishment.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Sheqer* (lie, deceit) — used three times in this section (vv. 8, 8, 10), forming a triple accusation: the scribes make the Torah into sheqer (v. 8), the pen is sheqer (v. 8), and the priests and prophets practice sheqer (v. 10). *Shever* (brokenness, fracture) will return in 8:21 applied to the prophet himself — the same wound that the false prophets minimized in the nation now breaks the genuine prophet who refuses to minimize it."
