        "body": "The divine oracle of verse 13 closes the indictment with agricultural covenant curse: the vine and fig tree — symbols not merely of agrarian prosperity but of the specific covenant blessings promised in Deuteronomy 8:8 and embodied in Solomon's reign (1 Kings 4:25) — produce nothing. The leaf withers. What the LORD gave He takes away. This is not random ecological disaster; it is the enacted reversal of the Abrahamic and Mosaic covenant promises.\n\nAt verse 14 the speaking voice shifts with arresting abruptness to the people themselves. 'Why are we sitting still?' is despair-driven, not repentance-driven. The move they contemplate — retreating into fortified cities — is purely survivalist. The theological diagnosis they give of their own condition (v. 14) is accurate: 'the LORD our God has doomed us and given us poisoned water to drink, for we have sinned against the LORD.' This is the most honest statement the people make in the chapter. They identify the agent (the LORD), the cause (they have sinned), and the consequence (doom and poison). But confession that names the sin without seeking the forgiver produces only despair, not rescue. They move from accurate diagnosis (v. 14) to fearful acknowledgment of failed hope (v. 15: waited for peace, hoped for healing, received terror) to passive reception of military sound (v. 16: the Babylonian cavalry already audible from Dan).\n\nThe Babylonian army's approach in verse 16 is rendered in sound-images: snorting (nachar), neighing (matshalah), the quaking of the whole land (raash). The enemy is not described visually — he is heard. The aural presentation heightens the terror because you cannot see where to run when the sound is already everywhere. And then God speaks again (v. 17) to close the section with an image drawn from the wilderness: 'I am sending serpents against you, adders for which there is no charm.' In Numbers 21, Israel was bitten by serpents for speaking against God and Moses; Moses fashioned a bronze serpent and those who looked at it lived. Here the charm — the ancient Near Eastern snake-charmer's art, and by implication any form of apotropaic ritual or prophetic intercession — will not work. The situation is beyond remedy by human religious technique.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Rosh* (poisoned, v. 14) — literally 'head' or 'venom/poison'; used in Deuteronomy 29:18 for the bitter root of idolatry and in Lamentations 3:5 for affliction. *Lachash* (charm, v. 17) — the whispered incantation of a snake charmer; Psalm 58:5 uses the same word for the charming of serpents. Its negation here removes the last ritual escape route."
